    <p>
      Summary of important ideas regarding the derivative of a linear function.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every linear function has a constant average rate of change on any possible interval.  For example, <m>f(x)=-3x+5</m> is a linear function with slope <m>-3</m>, and the average rate of change of <m>f</m> on any interval is <m>-3</m>.  The instantaneous rate of change of <m>f</m> at any input value will therefore also be <m>-3</m>, since the instantaneous rate of change is the limit of average rates of change.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            More generally, for any linear function of form <m>f(x) = mx + b</m>b, <m>f'(a) = m</m> for any choice of <m>a</m>.  Said differently, the value of the derivative of any linear function at any chosen input is the slope of the line.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

