    <p>
      Summary of important ideas regarding the derivative of the absolute value function.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Not every function has a derivative at every point.  For example, if <m>g(x)=|x|</m>, then <m>g'(0)</m> does not exist. 
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            One reason that <m>g'(0)</m> does not exist is that when we zoom in on the point <m>(0,0)</m> on the graph of <m>y=g(x)</m>, there is a sharp corner on the graph at which the function's slope <q>jumps</q> from <m>-1</m> to the left of <m>x=0</m> to <m>+1</m> to the right of <m>x = 0</m>.
 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

      <activity xml:id="sec-deriv-pt-DC-Act3">
        <statement>
          
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>f(x) = -2x^2 + 3x - 4</m>.  Use the limit definition of the derivative to determine <m>f'(1)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>g(x) = x^3</m>.  Use the limit definition of the derivative to determine the slope of the tangent line to <m>y = g(x)</m> at the point <m>(-1,-1)</m>.  Hint<fn><m>g(-1+h) = (-1+h)^3 = -1 + 3h - 3h^2 + h^3</m></fn>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>r(x) = \frac{2}{x+3}</m>. Use the limit definition of the derivative to determine the instantaneous rate of change of <m>r</m> at the instant <m>x = 0</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>p(x) = 2^x</m>.  The limit definition of the derivative shows that 
                <me>
                  p'(0) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{p(0+h) - p(0)}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{2^{0+h} - 2^0}{h} = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{2^h - 1}{h}
                </me>.
                Notice that there is no algebra that can be done to remove a factor of <m>h</m> from the numerator, so this limit can’t be evaluated exactly.  Use small values of <m>h</m> to find an estimate of <m>p'(0)</m> that is accurate to within <m>0.001</m>.  Then, plot <m>p(x)=2^x</m> and its tangent line at <m>(0,1)</m> to confirm that the estimate of <m>p'(0)</m> is reasonable.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>f(x) = \sqrt{x+1}</m>.  Use the limit definition of the derivative to determine <m>f'(3)</m>.  Hint <fn>To simplify the difference quotient, a helpful step is to multiply the numerator by <m>\frac{\sqrt{4+h}+2}{\sqrt{4+h}+2}</m></fn>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
